ğŸ”§ 4. COMMON ISSUES & SOLUTIONS
----------------------------
âŒ Error: "mount: wrong fs type"

Fix:

blkid /dev/sdb1
mkfs.xfs /dev/sdb1

âŒ Error: "mount: special device does not exist"

Fix:

lsblk
fdisk -l
udevadm settle

âŒ Error: machine stuck during boot because fstab entry is wrong

Fix by editing fstab in rescue mode:

mount -o remount,rw /
vim /etc/fstab


Add noauto temporarily or comment the broken line.

âŒ Error: "target is busy"

Fix:

lsof /data
fuser -km /data
umount /data

----------------------------
ğŸ§  5. INTERVIEW QUESTIONS (with Answers)
----------------------------
1. What is mounting in Linux?

Mounting means attaching a filesystem to a directory so the OS can access it.

2. What file is used for permanent mounting?
/etc/fstab

3. How to check which process is preventing unmount?
fuser -m /mountpoint
lsof /mountpoint

4. Difference between mount and unmount?

mount â†’ add filesystem

umount â†’ remove filesystem

5. How to mount ISO?
mount -o loop file.iso /mnt

6. What happens if fstab has a wrong entry?

The system may not boot.

7. How to mount NFS?
mount -t nfs server:/path /mnt

8. How to remount root filesystem read-write?
mount -o remount,rw /

----------------------------
ğŸ¢ 6. REAL COMPANY SCENARIOS (Very Common)
----------------------------
â­ Scenario A â€” Application server needs a separate /app mount

Company wants separate storage for application logs.

Solution:
fdisk /dev/sdb
mkfs.xfs /dev/sdb1
mkdir /app
mount /dev/sdb1 /app
echo "/dev/sdb1 /app xfs defaults 0 0" >> /etc/fstab

â­ Scenario B â€” Database (MySQL/PostgreSQL) needs separate storage

DB team asks for separate mount for /var/lib/mysql.

Steps:

Stop DB

Mount new disk

Copy old data

Update fstab

â­ Scenario C â€” Kubernetes/OpenShift storage

Storage team provides new disk for container logs.

Mount under:

/var/lib/containers
/var/lib/kubelet


Requires:

mount /dev/sdc1 /var/lib/containers

â­ Scenario D â€” Programmer accidentally deleted fstab entry

System fails to mount important disk â†’ website down.

Fix:

mount -a
vim /etc/fstab

â­ Scenario E â€” Backup team wants NFS mount

Mount backup storage:

mount -t nfs backupserver:/archive /mnt/backup


Add in fstab:

backupserver:/archive /mnt/backup  nfs  defaults 0 0



